<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-201-097 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 437 655</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  March 14 1991 pB1(W) pB1(E) 12 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>VDTs are said not to increase miscarriage risk. (Health) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Waldholz, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US National Institute of Occupational Safety and Healthreports that working long hours in front of a video displayterminal (VDT) does not increase the risk of miscarriage forpregnant women.andP;  The research group compared the miscarriage ratesof two groups: telephone operators using VDTs and those not usingVDTs.andP;  The miscarriage rate in the first three months was 15percent for VDT users and 16 percent for non-VDT users, astatistically insignificant difference.andP;  The study was based on882 pregnancies.andP;  The research group attributes higher miscarriagerates to smoking more than 20 cigarettes a day or consuming morethan eight alcoholic beverages a month.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     VDTsUnited States. National Institute for Occupational Safety andHealthReportsScientific ResearchOccupational Health.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>